Task 1

Create a histogram of life expectancy (i.e., including data from all 50 states).
Did you use binwidth = or bins = and how did you decide on the value?

ggplot(data = dat, mapping = aes(x=Life.Exp)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5) +
  xlab('Life Expectancy') +
  ylab('counts')

Task 2

Use group_by() and summary() to determine mean life expectancies and HS grad- uation rates for each region.

group_by(dat, Region) %>%
  summarise(avg_LE = mean(Life.Exp, na.rm = TRUE), 
            avg_HS_rate = mean(HS.Grad, na.rm = TRUE))

Task 3

Use frequency polygons to create histograms of life expectancy by color based on state region, both by count and using density.
Which do you prefer for these data and why?

I still preferred the counts one, because it’s obviously clear to show the difference.

#by counts
ggplot(data = dat, mapping = aes(Life.Exp, color = Region)) +
  geom_freqpoly(binwidth= 0.5) + 
  xlab("Life Expectancy") + 
  ylab("counts")

#by density
ggplot(data = dat, mapping = aes(Life.Exp, after_stat(density), color = Region)) +
  geom_freqpoly(binwidth= 0.5) + 
  xlab("Life Expectancy") + 
  ylab("density")

Task 4

Create conditional box plots of life expectancy by state region (i.e., using the same information as in the previous task).
What are the pros/cons to using boxplots vs frequency polygons here and in general?

Pros: it can clearly show the range of the data, and mean. cons: But the comparison between then is not clear.

ggplot(data = dat, mapping = aes(Region, Life.Exp)) +
  geom_boxplot() + 
  ylab("Life Expectancy") + 
  xlab("Region")

## Task 5 Replicate the last plot but also order the boxplots by their medians.

ggplot(data = dat, mapping = aes(x=reorder(Region, Life.Exp, FUN = median), y=Life.Exp)) +
  geom_boxplot() + 
  ylab("Life Expectancy") + 
  xlab("Region")

Task 6

Create a scatterplot of HS graduation rate on the horizontal axis and life expectancy on the vertical axis.

ggplot(data = dat, mapping = aes(x = HS.Grad, y = Life.Exp)) +
  geom_point() + 
  ylab("Life Expectancy") + 
  xlab("High School Graduation Rate")

Task 7

Replicate the scatterplot directly above using two-letter state abbreviations instead of points for plotting.

ggplot(data = dat, mapping = aes(x = HS.Grad, y = Life.Exp)) +
  geom_text(aes(label = abbrev)) + 
  ylab("Life Expectancy") + 
  xlab("High School Graduation Rate")

Task 8

Note that AK and NV are outlying. Use filter(), as in lines 163–169 of ’04_Code.R’, to color those two points blue.

temp <- dat%>% 
  filter(abbrev %in% c("AK", "NV"))

ggplot(data = dat, mapping = aes(x = HS.Grad, y = Life.Exp)) +
  geom_text(aes(label = abbrev)) + 
  geom_text(data = temp, mapping = aes(x=HS.Grad, y = Life.Exp, label = abbrev), color = "blue") +
  ylab("Life Expectancy") + 
  xlab("High School Graduation Rate")
